# 24_style_editor_dialog_full — substrate-layer suite for StyleEditorDialog
# (s201 m2).
#
# Substrate-style test per TESTING.md grandfather clause: every
# sub-test proves the substrate contract holds — abbrev resolves,
# verbs dispatch, queries read back. Round-trips on the value-bearing
# widgets, label read on the buttons.
#
# m2 migrated 12 raw widget sites in StyleEditorDialog to substrate,
# atop the s201 m1 lifetime conversion (the dialog is now a hide-on-
# close singleton owned by MainWindow, mirroring ThemeEditDialog's
# s200 m1 conversion). With the singleton lifetime, the substrate
# abbrevs register on first show() and stay registered for the app's
# lifetime — multiple opens of the Style Editor don't reconstruct
# anything, so this test runs identically on every reopen.
#
# No helper-threading instances this milestone — all 12 sites are
# single-instance migrations. The cap/join ToggleButton arrays are
# inline rather than factory-built; six explicit makes, six explicit
# migrations.
#
# DSL note: SpinButton-like queries on Scale return Double. Round-
# number literals in asserts need an explicit `.0` suffix.
#
# The tested abbrevs:
#
#   Identity section
#     Category dropdown    dlg_se_cat                  (DropDown)
#
#   Stroke section
#     Cap row              dlg_se_cb / cr / cs         (ToggleButtons)
#     Join row             dlg_se_jm / jr / jb         (ToggleButtons)
#
#   Shadow section (S98)
#     Enable check         dlg_se_sen                  (CheckButton)
#     Colour-alpha slider  dlg_se_sca                  (Scale)
#     Opacity slider       dlg_se_sop                  (Scale)
#
#   Button row
#     Cancel               dlg_se_cnc                  (Button — s201 m2)
#     OK                   dlg_se_ok                   (Button — s201 m2;
#                                                       set_name only in
#                                                       s199 m1 wave)
#
# Test protocol — FULLY SELF-DRIVING (s201 m3, narrated in s202 m2):
#
# Earlier draft (s201 m2 first cut) required the tester to manually
# open the Style Editor before running this script — the kebab menu's
# "+ New style" item isn't substrate-addressable. s201 m3 added the
# `do <action.name>` DSL verb that dispatches a Gio action by name,
# which IS what the menu item fires. The script could drive the whole
# flow, but the dialog opening was "magic" from a viewer's perspective
# — the kebab and menu item never appeared.
#
# s202 m2 lands the visual-narration foundation: `pnl_styles` is a
# registered Scriptable that publishes the panel's user outcomes by
# name. The prologue below shows the kebab opening, highlights the
# "New style" item, dismisses the kebab, then opens the dialog — the
# same sequence a real user performs. The assertion coverage doesn't
# change; only the prologue gains visible beats.
#
#   1. Open Curvz with a fresh / default document and project.
#   2. Open the Scripter window.
#   3. Load this script.
#   4. Run. The script narrates the kebab dance, opens the dialog via
#      `pnl_styles new_style`, runs every substrate assertion, then
#      closes the dialog via `dlg_se_cnc click` (which fires
#      StyleEditorDialog::on_cancel and discards the working buffer).
#
# Reopening across runs: with the s201 m1 singleton lifetime the
# dialog's widget tree survives close/hide, so a second run of this
# script reuses the same registered substrate objects and produces
# identical PASS results.

#[sub] Focus the Styles section. focus_section (s202 m5) is the
#[sub] composite move: collapse every inspector section, then open
#[sub] the ancestor chain. For Styles that's "Content" → "Styles" —
#[sub] both the group section and the leaf section open in one verb.
#[sub] Required pre-condition for show_kebab: the kebab button has
#[sub] an on-screen allocation only when both ancestors are visible.
#[sub] A collapsed Content group would hide the Styles section's
#[sub] allocation regardless of its own open flag, leaving the
#[sub] kebab unrendered and the popover fallback-positioned to the
#[sub] app's upper-right.

pnl_styles focus_section
sleep 400

#[sub] Open the kebab popover programmatically. The viewer sees the
#[sub] same menu a real user would see when clicking the kebab.

pnl_styles show_kebab
sleep 400

#[sub] Highlight the "+ New style" menu item. The Scriptable walks
#[sub] the popover's child tree to find the model button whose
#[sub] action-name matches "styles.create-empty", adds the
#[sub] .demo-highlight class for 600ms.

pnl_styles highlight_menuitem "create-empty"
sleep 600

#[sub] Close the popover. The kebab disappears like the user just
#[sub] clicked away — the actual menu-item click that opens the
#[sub] dialog happens via the Scriptable's new_style verb below,
#[sub] mirroring "user closed the kebab without picking, then the
#[sub] action fired anyway" — which IS what happens in the real
#[sub] activate-action path (Gtk auto-dismisses the popover when a
#[sub] menu item is activated).

pnl_styles hide_kebab

#[sub] Now open the dialog. Same outcome as a real menu-item click —
#[sub] action_create_empty runs, signal_request_style_editor fires,
#[sub] MainWindow constructs the dialog with StyleEditorDialog's
#[sub] show() path. The dialog appears non-modal so the Scripter
#[sub] retains focus and the rest of the script can drive the
#[sub] dialog's substrate widgets.

pnl_styles new_style

#[sub] Button row — Cancel / OK labels.
#[sub] OK is not clicked from this script (would commit a stub style
#[sub] to the project). Cancel is clicked at the very end to close
#[sub] the dialog cleanly. Label readbacks are enough substrate-
#[sub] contract coverage here.

assert dlg_se_cnc label == "Cancel"
assert dlg_se_ok  label == "OK"

#[sub] Category DropDown — count + selected + text round-trip.
#[sub] The dropdown's model is rebuilt per show() from m_category_order
#[sub] which has at minimum "(uncategorised)" first and the
#[sub] "+ New category…" sentinel last. On a fresh project with no
#[sub] user-defined style categories, count is exactly 2; if the
#[sub] tester runs this script against a project that has accumulated
#[sub] user categories, the count assert will fail and can be skipped
#[sub] — the selected/text assertions below still prove the substrate
#[sub] contract.

assert dlg_se_cat count == 2
dlg_se_cat set 0
assert dlg_se_cat selected == 0
assert dlg_se_cat text == "(uncategorised)"

#[sub] Cap row — ToggleButton labels are empty (icon-only) but
#[sub] active/set round-trips work the same as labelled toggles.
#[sub] Cap row is a set_group radio: setting one true forces the
#[sub] others false. We exercise all three to prove the substrate
#[sub] path fires signal_toggled on each.

dlg_se_cb set true
assert dlg_se_cb active == true
assert dlg_se_cr active == false
assert dlg_se_cs active == false

dlg_se_cr set true
assert dlg_se_cr active == true
assert dlg_se_cb active == false
assert dlg_se_cs active == false

dlg_se_cs set true
assert dlg_se_cs active == true
assert dlg_se_cb active == false
assert dlg_se_cr active == false

# Restore butt (the LineCap::Butt default) for tidiness.
dlg_se_cb set true

#[sub] Join row — same set_group radio shape as Cap.

dlg_se_jm set true
assert dlg_se_jm active == true
assert dlg_se_jr active == false
assert dlg_se_jb active == false

dlg_se_jr set true
assert dlg_se_jr active == true
assert dlg_se_jm active == false
assert dlg_se_jb active == false

dlg_se_jb set true
assert dlg_se_jb active == true
assert dlg_se_jm active == false
assert dlg_se_jr active == false

# Restore miter (the LineJoin::Miter default) for tidiness.
dlg_se_jm set true

#[sub] Shadow enable CheckButton round-trip.
#[sub] Toggling the enable check triggers the sensitivity-slave
#[sub] lambda which greys / un-greys every other shadow widget.
#[sub] The substrate set verb fires signal_toggled, so the slave
#[sub] runs even from a script-driven flip.

dlg_se_sen set true
assert dlg_se_sen active == true
dlg_se_sen set false
assert dlg_se_sen active == false

#[sub] Shadow Colour-alpha Scale — range + round-trip.
#[sub] Adjustment is 0..100 mapped to 0..1 internally; the slider's
#[sub] value is the displayed integer percentage.

assert dlg_se_sca min == 0.0
assert dlg_se_sca max == 100.0
dlg_se_sca set 75.0
assert dlg_se_sca value == 75.0
dlg_se_sca set 50.0
assert dlg_se_sca value == 50.0

#[sub] Shadow Opacity Scale — range + round-trip.
#[sub] Same 0..100 percentage shape as the colour-alpha slider.

assert dlg_se_sop min == 0.0
assert dlg_se_sop max == 100.0
dlg_se_sop set 80.0
assert dlg_se_sop value == 80.0
dlg_se_sop set 100.0
assert dlg_se_sop value == 100.0

#[sub] Close the dialog. Clicking Cancel discards the working buffer
#[sub] and fires StyleEditorDialog::on_cancel → close() → hide-on-
#[sub] close. The dialog's substrate widgets stay alive (singleton
#[sub] lifetime); a subsequent `do styles.create-empty` reopens with
#[sub] a fresh seed and sync_from_working repopulates every widget.

dlg_se_cnc click

#[sub] Done. If every line PASSed, every m2-migrated abbrev resolves
#[sub] in the registry, dispatches its verbs correctly, and queries
#[sub] read back the live state. 12 new substrate widgets across one
#[sub] dialog — and StyleEditorDialog now joins ThemeEditDialog with
#[sub] zero raw substrate-class widgets remaining. The dialog tail
#[sub] is closed; zero heap-allocated dialogs remain in Curvz.
